<div class="examples-page">
  <h1>Example Workflows</h1>
  <p class="subtitle">
    See what happens when you give the swarm a prompt. Each example shows the input,
    which agents activate, and what code gets produced.
  </p>

  <!-- Example 1: Simple Page -->
  <div class="example-card simple">
    <div class="example-label">Example 1</div>
    <h2>Add a Simple Page</h2>

    <div class="prompt-block">
      <span class="prompt-prefix">&gt; </span>Add a Contact page with a heading, a paragraph of text, and a link back to the home page.
    </div>

    <p><strong>Agents activated:</strong></p>
    <ul class="agent-list">
      <li><strong>Architect</strong> Reads prompt, decides only Controllers + Views are needed</li>
      <li><strong>Controllers</strong> Adds route, creates ContactController</li>
      <li><strong>Views</strong> Creates the ERB template with heading, text, and link</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Files created:</strong></p>
    <div class="files-list">
      <span class="mod-file">config/routes.rb</span> &mdash; added route<br>
      <span class="new-file">app/controllers/contact_controller.rb</span> &mdash; new<br>
      <span class="new-file">app/views/contact/index.html.erb</span> &mdash; new
    </div>

    <div class="takeaway">
      The swarm only activates the agents it needs. No database work means the Models agent stays idle.
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Example 2: Full-Stack Blog -->
  <div class="example-card fullstack">
    <div class="example-label">Example 2</div>
    <h2>Full-Stack Blog</h2>

    <div class="prompt-block">
      <span class="prompt-prefix">&gt; </span>Create a Blog. A post has a title and body. Include model with validations, CRUD controller, all views, and tests.
    </div>

    <p><strong>Agents activated:</strong></p>
    <ul class="agent-list">
      <li><strong>Architect</strong> Recognizes full-stack work, activates four agents</li>
      <li><strong>Models</strong> Creates migration, Post model with validations</li>
      <li><strong>Controllers</strong> Adds RESTful routes, creates PostsController with CRUD</li>
      <li><strong>Views</strong> Creates index, show, new, edit templates + form partial</li>
      <li><strong>Tests</strong> Creates model and controller tests</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Files created:</strong></p>
    <div class="files-list">
      <span class="new-file">db/migrate/..._create_posts.rb</span> &mdash; migration<br>
      <span class="new-file">app/models/post.rb</span> &mdash; model<br>
      <span class="mod-file">config/routes.rb</span> &mdash; added resources :posts<br>
      <span class="new-file">app/controllers/posts_controller.rb</span> &mdash; CRUD controller<br>
      <span class="new-file">app/views/posts/index.html.erb</span> &mdash; listing<br>
      <span class="new-file">app/views/posts/show.html.erb</span> &mdash; detail view<br>
      <span class="new-file">app/views/posts/new.html.erb</span> &mdash; new form<br>
      <span class="new-file">app/views/posts/edit.html.erb</span> &mdash; edit form<br>
      <span class="new-file">app/views/posts/_form.html.erb</span> &mdash; shared partial<br>
      <span class="new-file">test/models/post_test.rb</span> &mdash; model tests<br>
      <span class="new-file">test/controllers/posts_controller_test.rb</span> &mdash; controller tests
    </div>

    <div class="takeaway">
      One prompt produces a complete feature across all Rails layers, following conventions like RESTful routes, strong parameters, and form partials.
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Example 3: Background Jobs -->
  <div class="example-card jobs">
    <div class="example-label">Example 3</div>
    <h2>Background Jobs</h2>

    <div class="prompt-block">
      <span class="prompt-prefix">&gt; </span>When a new user signs up, send them a welcome email in the background. Create the User model, mailer, and job.
    </div>

    <p><strong>Agents activated:</strong></p>
    <ul class="agent-list">
      <li><strong>Architect</strong> Identifies model, async processing, and test concerns</li>
      <li><strong>Models</strong> Creates User migration + model with after_create callback</li>
      <li><strong>Jobs</strong> Creates SendWelcomeEmailJob and WelcomeMailer</li>
      <li><strong>Tests</strong> Creates model, job, and mailer tests</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Files created:</strong></p>
    <div class="files-list">
      <span class="new-file">db/migrate/..._create_users.rb</span> &mdash; migration<br>
      <span class="new-file">app/models/user.rb</span> &mdash; model with callback<br>
      <span class="new-file">app/jobs/send_welcome_email_job.rb</span> &mdash; background job<br>
      <span class="new-file">app/mailers/welcome_mailer.rb</span> &mdash; mailer<br>
      <span class="new-file">app/views/welcome_mailer/welcome.html.erb</span> &mdash; email template<br>
      <span class="new-file">test/models/user_test.rb</span> &mdash; model tests<br>
      <span class="new-file">test/jobs/send_welcome_email_job_test.rb</span> &mdash; job tests<br>
      <span class="new-file">test/mailers/welcome_mailer_test.rb</span> &mdash; mailer tests
    </div>

    <div class="takeaway">
      The swarm handles cross-cutting concerns naturally. Models creates the trigger, Jobs creates the async work, and Tests covers everything.
    </div>
  </div>

